<br><br>
<br>The <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Polymer" rel="noopener" class="external-link" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Polymer" target="_blank">polymer</a> is an existing <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chemical_substance" rel="noopener" class="external-link" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chemical_substance" target="_blank">substance</a> with properties, structure and possible roles in the cell or otherwise

<br>The sequence is a limited <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Representation_(arts)" rel="noopener" class="external-link" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Representation_(arts)" target="_blank">representation</a> of the existing <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Molecule" rel="noopener" class="external-link" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Molecule" target="_blank">molecule</a>.
<br>Only the sequential order of the <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Residue_(chemistry)" rel="noopener" class="external-link" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Residue_(chemistry)" target="_blank">residues</a> is portrayed.

<br>Implications of that sequential order are up to the reader of the sequence.




<br>The way residues are represented depends on the intended use or volition of the sequence coder.
<br>
<img alt="Pasted image 20240904152337.png" src="lib\media\pasted-image-20240904152337.png">
<img alt="Pasted image 20240904152412.png" src="lib\media\pasted-image-20240904152412.png">
<br><br>
<br>The sequence as an <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Information" rel="noopener" class="external-link" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Information" target="_blank">information</a> container.

<br>The sequential order of residues is the information contained


<br>Other features conveying information

<br>Modifications to the residues
<br>Molecule folding
<br>Association with other <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="https://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/concomitant" rel="noopener" class="external-link" href="https://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/concomitant" target="_blank">concomitant</a> molecules


<br>How to measure the information content in a <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="https://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/naive" rel="noopener" class="external-link" href="https://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/naive" target="_blank">naive</a> approach?

<br>Deviation to a random result
<br>Looking at the sequence as a sequence of "choices" between available states
<br>Assessing the degree of "organization" conveyed by the sequence


<br>Information content varies throughout gene expression

